properties.name: La Cartoucherie
properties.description: Posted by RadananitaLa CartoucherieA group of five 19th-century military buildings liberated by soixante-huitards and converted into theaters. I\'m glad my daughter went to the nursery school the actors\' day-care center evolved into at the time she did, when it was called the Maison des Enfants and not the too Lacanian Petits Terriens.

properties.name: Light My Fire
properties.description: Posted by RadananitaWesttown, PAThe year must be 1967, though all I know is that I am ecstatic to have moved back to a farm in then-rural Pennsylvania after three or four miserable years i Cleveland Heights. I am back with my friend Tater whom I\'ve known since first grade. Tater is blessed with an interesting variety of big brothers. Seventh-graders, we are riding in the eldest brother\'s automobile, probably a Volvo, and "Light My Fire" comes on the car radio. The immortal baroque guitar licks flame around our brains like Jim Morrison\'s sexy curly hair. Once again, in the space of a three-minute single, a number-one song, our lives change forever.

properties.name: Louie Louie
properties.description: Posted by Radananita3908 MayfieldThe one good thing about the four angry years I spent in this suburb from ages eight to eleven was discovering rock music. I was totally uncool and only had uncool girlfriends. We used to listen to "Louie Louie" with headphones on in an effort to hear the dirty parts. The year was 1965. I have a feeling it must have been the Paul Revere and the Raiders version.

properties.name: Rue Jeanne d'Arc, St. Mandé
properties.description: Posted by RadananitaRue Jeanne d\'Arc, St. MandéThis is where I was when I heard about the Twin Towers. I was phoning a translation client who owed me money. When they told me that a plane had crashed into the World Trade Center, and that there was nothing else on the news, and they were all riveted to the TV set in the office (it\'s a film translation company) I initially thought they were just trying to get out of writing the check by making up a cockamamie story. Then I saw the television in the bar-tabac Le Narwhal.

properties.name: So Happy Together by the Turtles
properties.description: Posted by Radananita3970 Mayfield Road, Cleveland Heights, OHIt\'s the mid-1960s, and I am gradually and bitterly habituating myself to life in a suburb of Cleveland, Ohio. Riding in the Volkswagen bug of my mother and her new husband, who has presumably replaced my father, we are listening to AM radio when my favorite song comes on. My stepfather remarks that he has read that rock music exerts a strange and evil power over young people by locking into the rhythm of their heartbeats. I silently vow eternal allegiance to youth and rock. The Turtles concert was the first live music event I had ever attended aside from the Philadelphia Orchestra Young People\'s Concert in Robin Hood Dell. I was enchanted when singer Mark Vollman - the fat one, I think - lifted up his t-shirt and actually swung his hairy belly at the audience in time to the music. My mother was disgusted when I told her about this.
